        public static String getClassPath(Class<?> c)
        Find the path from which a given class was loaded.
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        the path of the .class file for the given class or null (e.g. if the class is anonymous).

      • getResourcePath

        public static String getResourcePath(Class<?> c,
                                     String name)
        Find the path to a resource relative to the location of class c. Example: Assume class C was loaded from file someLocation/C.class and there is a subfolder someLocation/resources/ that contains an image 'lenna.jpg'. Then the absolute path to this image is obtained by String path = getResourcePath(C.class, "resources/lenna.jpg");
        Parameters:
        c - anchor class
        name - name of the resource to be found
        Returns:
        the path for the resource or null if not found.

      • getResourceStream

        public static InputStream getResourceStream(Class<?> c,
                                            String name)
        Finds a resource relative to the location of class c and returns a stream to read from. Example: Assume class C was loaded from file someLocation/C.class and there is a subfolder someLocation/resources/ that contains an image 'lenna.jpg'. Then the input stream for reading this this image is obtained by InputStream strm = getResourceStream(C.class, "resources/lenna.jpg"); Use this method to access resources stored in a JAR file!
        Parameters:
        c - anchor class
        name - name of the resource to be found
        Returns:
        a stream for reading the resource or null if not found.

      • checkResource

        public static boolean checkResource(String classname,
                                    String recourcePath)

        Parameters:

      • listResources

        public static Path[] listResources(Class<?> theClass,
                                   String relPath)
        Use this method to obtain the paths to all files in a directory located relative to the specified class. This should work in an ordinary file system as well as a (possibly nested) JAR file.
        Parameters:
        theClass - class whose source location specifies the root
        relPath - path relative to the root
        Returns:
        a sequence of paths or null if the specified path is not a directory
